126 // A fixed element depth limit is problematic. There needs to be a
127 // limit to avoid a stack overflow. However, that limit varies per
128 // system, and the capacity of the stack. On the other hand, it's a trivial
129 // attack that can result from ill, malicious, or even correctly formed XML,
130 // so there needs to be a limit in place.
131 static const int TINYXML2_MAX_ELEMENT_DEPTH = 500;
